<hl>
<seg id=1> Two South Korean soldiers fled North Korea after 45 years imprisonment. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Reuters, Seoul According to the South Korean National Security Planning Department the day before yesterday, two soldiers who were listed in the casualty list during the Korean War fled North Korea after at least 45 years imprisonment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The National Security Planning Department made a statement that 67-year-old Jin Fuji and 71-year-old Piao Dongyi returned to South Korea recently through a third country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The statement said that both of them were seized during the war by the Chinese soldiers near the border between South Korea and North Korea in the Northeast area. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The statement said that both of them were enslaved in a mine in North Korea before their escape. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> After the War from 1950 to 1953, the Ministry of Defense of South Korea listed thousands of the missing soldiers' names into the casualty list, and Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi were among them. </seg>
<seg id=7> South Korea and North Korea finally signed a cease-fire agreement, but not a formal peace treaty. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> South Korea and North Korea are still waging war in technology. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Out of people's imagination, the two men became relatives by marriage during their imprisonment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The statement said that Jin Fuji's second son Jin Lingqiu married with Piao Dongyi's fourth daughter Piao Zhengxin in April 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> The statement didn't give a further explanation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> An official of the National Security Planning Department said that Jin Fuji and Piao Dongyi had been arrested and questioned by the government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> The Minister of Defense once addressed that about 20,000 soldiers were missing during the war, and the Minister of Defense believed that some of them were still alive. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> This April, an escaped prisoner of war said that he knew there were 56 South Korean soldiers imprisoned in North Korea at present. </seg>
</p>
